"Cou ̂teaux M.-M., Bottner P., Berg B.","Litter decomposition, climate and liter quality",1995,"Trends in Ecology & Evolution","10","2",,"63","66",,,10.1016/S0169-5347(00)88978-8,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0028976631&partnerID=40&md5=cd60917b7a3900137c850f4def4e28a4","Centre d'Ecologie Fonctionnelle et Evolutive, Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, BP 5051, Route de Mende, F-34033 Montpellier Cedex, France; Dept of Forest Soils, Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences, PO Box 7001, S-750 07 Uppsala, Sweden","Cou ̂teaux, M.-M., Centre d'Ecologie Fonctionnelle et Evolutive, Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, BP 5051, Route de Mende, F-34033 Montpellier Cedex, France; Bottner, P., Centre d'Ecologie Fonctionnelle et Evolutive, Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, BP 5051, Route de Mende, F-34033 Montpellier Cedex, France; Berg, B., Dept of Forest Soils, Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences, PO Box 7001, S-750 07 Uppsala, Sweden","Litter decomposition is controlled by three main factors: climate, litter quality and the nature and abundance of the decomposing organisms. Climate is the dominant factor in areas subjected to unfavourable weather conditions, whereas litter quality largely prevails as the regulator under favourable conditions. Litter quality remains important until the late decomposition stages through its effects on humus formation. Interest in the role of litter decomposition in the global carbon cycle has increased recently since (1) increased atmospheric carbon dioxide will probably affect the chemical quality of litter (especially nitrogen content), and (2) global warming may enhance decomposition rates. © 1995 Elsevier Science Ltd.",,"carbon budget; carbon cycle; carbon dioxide enrichment; climate; decomposition; decomposition rate; global carbon cycle; global warming; humus; litter; litter decomposition",,,,,,"Raich, Schlesinger, (1992) Tellus, 44 B, pp. 81-99; Berg, Nutrient release from litter and humus in coniferous forest soils—a mini review (1986) Scandinavian Journal of Forest Research, 1, pp. 359-369; Meyer, (1994) Ecol. Stud., 99, pp. 67-96; Fog, (1988) Biol. Rev., 63, pp. 433-462; Couˆteaux, Bottner, (1993) Beyond the Biomass: Compositional and Functional Analysis of Soil Microbial Communities, pp. 159-172. , K. Ritz, J. Dighton, K.E. Giller, Wiley; Virzo De Santo, (1993) Soil Biol. Biochem., 25, pp. 1423-1433; Orsborne, Macauley, (1988) Soil Biol. Biochem., 20, pp. 369-375; Meentemeyer, Macroclimate the Lignin Control of Litter Decomposition Rates (1978) Ecology, 59, pp. 465-472; Meentemeyer, Berg, Regional variation in rate of mass loss of Pinus sylvestris needle litter in Swedish pine forests as influenced by climate and litter quality (1986) Scandinavian Journal of Forest Research, 1, pp. 167-180; Berg, (1993) Biogeochemistry, 20, pp. 127-153; Berg, Staaf, Wessen, Decomposition and nutrient release in needle litter from nitrogen‐fertilized scots pine (pinus sylvestris)stands (1987) Scandinavian Journal of Forest Research, 2, pp. 399-415; Berg, Johnasson, McClaugherty, (1993) Can. J. Bot., 71, pp. 680-692; Berg, Ekbohm, (1991) Can. J. Bot., 69, pp. 1449-1456; Moore, (1984) Ecology, 65, pp. 299-308; Taylor, Parkinson, (1988) Soil Biol. Biochem., 20, pp. 647-656; Coxson, Parkinson, (1987) Soil Biol. Biochem., 19, pp. 49-59; Schaefer, Steinberger, Whitford, (1985) Oecologia, 65, pp. 382-386; Steinberger, Whitford, (1988) Oecologia, 75, pp. 61-66; Vossbrinck, Coleman, Woolley, Abiotic and Biotic Factors in Litter Decomposition in a Sermiarid Grassland (1979) Ecology, 60, pp. 265-271; Montana, Ezcurra, Carrillo, Delhoume, (1988) J. Arid. Environ., 14, pp. 55-60; Moorhead, Reynolds, (1989) J. Arid Environ., 16, pp. 157-163; Bargali, Singh, Singh, (1993) Soil Biol. Biochem., 25, pp. 1731-1738; Tanner, The Decomposition of Leaf Litter in Jamaican Montane Rain Forests (1981) The Journal of Ecology, 69, pp. 263-273; Cuevas, Medina, (1988) Oecologi